value.value: Activin receptor type-2B (512 aa, ~58 kDa) is encoded by the human ACVR2B gene. This protein plays a role in protein kinase-dependent signaling and embryonic development.
A gene that encodes a proteolytic enzyme that depends on a metal ion to catalyze peptide bond hydrolysis.
This gene is involved in the inhibition of angiogenesis and cell proliferation.

label.value: A Disintegrin and Metalloprotease with Thrombospondin Motifs 1

value.value: A disintegrin and metalloproteinase with thrombospondin motifs 1 (967 aa, ~105 kDa) is encoded by the human ADAMTS1 gene. This protein plays a role in both proteolysis and integrin-mediated signaling.
This gene plays a role in apoptosis and development.

label.value: A Disintegrin and Metalloprotease with Thrombospondin Motifs 9

value.value: A disintegrin and metalloproteinase with thrombospondin motifs 9 (1935 aa, ~216 kDa) is encoded by the human ADAMTS9 gene. This protein is involved in the degradation of proteoglycans.

Vesicant compounds originally used as chemical warfare agents. At high temperatures, is in vapor form and readily absorbed through the skin, eyes, airway, and GI tract.  It reacts with DNA, RNA, and proteins, compromising normal cell function.
This gene is involved in cellular adhesion and modulates cadherin interactions.
Enzyme Genes encode Enzymes, biological molecules (usually proteins) that possess catalytic activity. Catalytic RNA and catalytic DNA molecules have also been identified. (NCI)
Lyase Genes encode Lyases, a class of enzymes that catalyze the hydration-dehydration cleavage of C-C, C-O, C-N, and other bonds by means other than hydrolysis or oxidation. (NCI)
This gene is involved in nucleotide metabolism and signal transduction.
This gene plays a regulatory role in the growth and proliferation of several cell types.
Alpha-1A adrenergic receptor (466 aa, ~51 kDa) is encoded by the human ADRA1A gene. This protein is involved in smooth muscle contraction, cell proliferation, apoptosis and signal transduction.
This gene plays a role in the regulation of neurotransmitter release from nerves and neurons in the central nervous system.

Alpha-2A adrenergic receptor (465 aa, ~51 kD) is a cell motility protein that is encoded by the human ADRA2A gene. This protein plays a role in actin cytoskeletal organization, cell motility, regulation of cell proliferation and signal transduction.
This gene is involved in transcriptional regulation and G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction.
Alpha-2B adrenergic receptor (450 aa, ~50 kDa) is encoded by the human ADRA2B gene. This protein plays a role in catacholamine-dependent signaling.

A mustard compound that gets converted to an active mustard alkylating agent at a tumor site, causing DNA cross-linking. These compounds may be used in antibody-directed enzyme prodrug therapy (ADEPT).
This gene plays a role in apoptosis and in ligand-binding interactions.
This gene plays several roles in cellular functions specific to the T-cell.

Expressed in effector tissues innervated by postganglionic sympathetic adrenergic fibers, Beta Adrenergic Receptor Genes encode Beta Adrenergic Receptors, one of two major classes of adrenergic receptors (alpha and beta) based on their reactions to norepinephrine and epinephrine, on cellular effects of receptor activation, and on relative affinities and reactions to synthetic blocking or stimulating agents. Beta-adrenergic receptors respond to blocking agents such as propranolol and to activating agents such as isoproterenol. Beta-1 type receptors mediate lipolysis and increase cardiac rate and force of contraction; beta-2 type receptor activation promotes bronchial and vascular smooth muscle relaxation. When coupled to adenylate cyclase through Gs protein, Beta Adrenergic Receptor stimulation results in increased intracellular cyclic AMP. (NCI)
This gene is involved in maintaining the integrity and rate of G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction.
This gene plays a role in cytoskeletal remodeling.

Ligand Binding Protein Genes encode Ligand Binding Proteins, a large class of diverse proteins for which a major function appears to be (typically high affinity) binding of some ligand for solubility, transport, bioactivity regulation, or other nonenzymatic process. Ligand interaction often alters protein molecular conformation and function. (NCI)
This gene plays a role in cytoskeletal regulation and cellular adhesion.
Beta-2 adrenergic receptor (413 aa, ~47 kDa) is encoded by the human ADRB2 gene. This protein is involved in both catecholamine binding and G protein-coupled receptor signaling.

RNA Binding Proteins temporarily and non-covalently interact through intermolecular physical forces of attraction and spatial complementarity with RNA in a sequence-dependent or -independent fashion for transport, catalysis, localization, or modification of function.

label.value: ATP-Binding Cassette Sub-Family B Member 6, Mitochondrial

value.value: ATP-binding cassette sub-family B member 6, mitochondrial (842 aa, ~94 kDa) is encoded by the human ABCB6 gene. This protein is involved in ATP-dependent transport of heme and porphyrin into the mitochondrion.

A group of mycotoxins, which are most commonly produced by Aspergillus flavus and A. parasiticus, and their toxic metabolites that are comprised of a fused coumarin-bis(dihydrofuran) ring structure, with potential acute and chronic toxic effects. Acute exposure to high levels of aflatoxins can cause liver damage. Chronic aflatoxin exposure results in an increased risk for liver cancer potentially caused by DNA intercalation and epoxide-mediated alkylation of nucleobases by aflatoxin metabolites, leading to increased levels of DNA damage, which may cause mutations.

Any substance that inhibits glutamate-cysteine ligase (gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase), an enzyme that catalyzes the ATP-dependent condensation of cysteine and glutamate to form the dipeptide gamma-glutamylcysteine, the rate-limiting step in the biosynthesis of glutathione. Since glutathione is critical in protecting cells against oxidative stress, its depletion results in free radical-induced apoptosis.
ABL interactor 2 (513 aa, ~56 kDa) is encoded by the human ABI2 gene. This protein plays a role in the regulation of both signal transduction and cell growth.
This gene plays a role in neural development and regulation of transcription.
This gene plays a regulatory role in the propagation of pro-apoptotic events.
This gene is involved in signal transduction and plays a role in insulin-mediated glucose uptake.
This gene is involved in signal transduction and cell cycle regulation.
This gene plays a role in signal transduction and modulates synaptic transmission.
This gene plays a role in signal transduction and angiogenesis.
This gene is involved in signal transduction and protein trafficking.
This gene plays a role in biosynthesis, cell differentiation and intercellular communication.
This gene is involved in the detoxification of xenobiotics.
An agent that inhibits the differentiation or maturation of cells, specifically neoplastic cells.
This gene is involved in cell cycle regulation.
This gene plays a role in blood vessel maturation and stability.
This gene is involved in vascular remodeling.
This gene plays a role in gonadal development.
This gene is involved in the transcription of ribosomal RNA genes.
This gene is involved in hormonal signaling and inflammation.
This gene is involved in the regulation of both function and survival of dopaminergic neurons.
This gene is involved in signal transduction and cell cycle regulation.
